<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="612">
Etymology Gr 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181982" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole dasypyx Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole dasypyx Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="612" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dasypyx">dasypyx</taxonomicName>
, hairy rump, referring to the dense pilosity of the gaster.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="612">
Diagnosis Major: distinguished within the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33947" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="612" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatissima">punctatissima</taxonomicName>
group by the combination of the 3-lobed promesonotal profile in side view, with the mesonotal (rearmost) convexity flat-topped; long, robust propodeal spine; completely rugulose posterior half of the head, reaching all the way to the occiput; completely foveolate and opaque first gastral tergite; and dense pilosity. Minor: head, mesosoma, and waist entirely foveolate and opaque; occiput narrow, with a very thin nuchal collar. Both castes are yellow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="612">measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.96, HL 0.94, SL 0.66, EL 0.16, PW 0.40. Paratype minor: HW 0.46, HL 0.54, SL 0.68, EL 0.10, PW 0.32. color Major and minor: concolorous medium yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
